    "summary": "The Mozambican Civil War lasted from 1977 to 1992, devastating one of Africa's poorest countries in the decade following independence from Portugal. The war pitted the FRELIMO government, which had led Mozambique to independence and established a Marxist one-party state, against RENAMO, a rebel movement initially created by Rhodesia and later sustained by apartheid South Africa as a destabilization tool against the socialist government that was supporting anti-apartheid movements in southern Africa.\n\nRENAMO's tactics were characterized by extreme brutality against civilians, including systematic mutilation, village destruction, forced recruitment of child soldiers, and attacks on schools and health clinics. These methods made normal economic life impossible across wide areas of the country. By the end of the conflict, approximately one million people had died, five million had been internally displaced, and Mozambique's already limited infrastructure lay in ruins.\n\nPeace negotiations gained momentum after South Africa ended its apartheid regime and withdrew support from RENAMO. The Rome General Peace Accords of October 1992, mediated by the Community of Sant'Egidio, ended the war. Mozambique subsequently held successful multiparty elections and began a slow but steady economic recovery. The country became a widely cited example of successful post-conflict reconstruction, aided by substantial international support.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mozambican_Civil_War",
